<catsoop-section>Instructions</catsoop-section>

1. If we are using playing cards, we will fold them from the centre so that the card can be placed perpendicular to the surface. Otherwise we can use domino pieces.

2. First we arrange dominoes for the AND gate. Standing domino represents **1** and fallen domino represents **0**.

3. Put two dominoes for input. Arrange all the dominoes such that we will get the result: if both inputs are 1 then the result will be 1. If any one input is 0 then the result is still 0. Here we use black colour for input and white colour for output.

<center>
<img src="COURSE/architecture/domino_computer/domino_computer_3.png" alt="AND Gate Setup 1" height="300"/>
<img src="COURSE/architecture/domino_computer/domino_computer_4.png" alt="AND Gate Setup 2" height="300"/>
</center>

4. Now give the inputs by pushing the dominoes slightly and see the result.

5. Repeat the process for other gates.

<catsoop-section>What's Happening</catsoop-section>

Here we have arranged the dominoes so that when we push both input A and B, the dominoes of C also fall down. If we push only one (A or B), the others will block the way and white dominoes will not fall down. This is a physical **AND gate**.

Computers use these gates to understand and process binary numbers. In binary, instead of using 1, 10, 100, 1000... as our values (which are POWERS of 10), we instead use POWERS of 2. These are 1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32... (doubling every time). With these, we can represent any number, and we will only ever need 0 or 1 in each column.

**Example:**
$$101101_2 = 45_{10} = (1 \times 32) + (0 \times 16) + (1 \times 8) + (1 \times 4) + (0 \times 2) + (1 \times 1)$$

